{"parse":{"title":"Tyg","pageid":1867662,"revid":823798572,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><div role=\"note\" class=\"hatnote navigation-not-searchable\">\"TYG\" redirects here. For a Swiss band also known as TYG, see <a href=\"/wiki/The_Young_Gods\" title=\"The Young Gods\">The Young Gods</a>.</div>\n<div class=\"thumb tright\"><div class=\"thumbinner\" style=\"width:222px;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Tyg,_George_Richardson,_Wrotham,_Kent,_dated_1651_-_Nelson-Atkins_Museum_of_Art_-_DSC08805.JPG\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/ba/Tyg%2C_George_Richardson%2C_Wrotham%2C_Kent%2C_dated_1651_-_Nelson-Atkins_Museum_of_Art_-_DSC08805.JPG/220px-Tyg%2C_George_Richardson%2C_Wrotham%2C_Kent%2C_dated_1651_-_Nelson-Atkins_Museum_of_Art_-_DSC08805.JPG\" width=\"220\" height=\"230\" class=\"thumbimage\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/ba/Tyg%2C_George_Richardson%2C_Wrotham%2C_Kent%2C_dated_1651_-_Nelson-Atkins_Museum_of_Art_-_DSC08805.JPG/330px-Tyg%2C_George_Richardson%2C_Wrotham%2C_Kent%2C_dated_1651_-_Nelson-Atkins_Museum_of_Art_-_DSC08805.JPG 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/ba/Tyg%2C_George_Richardson%2C_Wrotham%2C_Kent%2C_dated_1651_-_Nelson-Atkins_Museum_of_Art_-_DSC08805.JPG/440px-Tyg%2C_George_Richardson%2C_Wrotham%2C_Kent%2C_dated_1651_-_Nelson-Atkins_Museum_of_Art_-_DSC08805.JPG 2x\" data-file-width=\"1768\" data-file-height=\"1846\" /></a>  <div class=\"thumbcaption\"><div class=\"magnify\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Tyg,_George_Richardson,_Wrotham,_Kent,_dated_1651_-_Nelson-Atkins_Museum_of_Art_-_DSC08805.JPG\" class=\"internal\" title=\"Enlarge\"></a></div>Tyg made by George Richardson, Wrotham, Kent, dated 1651</div></div></div>\n<p>A <b>tyg</b> (or <b>tig</b>) is a large English pottery <a href=\"/wiki/Mug\" title=\"Mug\">mug</a> with three or more <a href=\"/wiki/Handle_(grip)\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Handle (grip)\">handles</a> dividing the rim into sections for several drinkers. These tall, black-glazed, red-bodied drinking vessels were produced from the 15th century through the first half of the 17th century, peaking in popularity during the 16th and 17th centuries.  Some were made with as many as nine handles. <sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup>  The multiple handles also allow hot drinks to be passed around without pain.\n</p><p>Tygs were made in large quantities at <a href=\"/wiki/Wrotham\" title=\"Wrotham\">Wrotham</a> in <a href=\"/wiki/Kent\" title=\"Kent\">Kent</a> and in many <a href=\"/wiki/Staffordshire\" title=\"Staffordshire\">Staffordshire</a> factories. Examples have surfaced at 17th-century American colonial sites, as well as in the UK.<sup id=\"cite_ref-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup>  There are also examples of Japanese and German tygs.\n</p><p>Many of the leading names in Staffordshire and Worcester area have manufactured miniature three handled tygs that stand proud at only 1 to 1 7/10 inches in size.  Most were probably used for decoration rather than drinking, as many of them are exquisitely painted.  They are widely collected.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Frilly-based_tyg\">Frilly-based tyg</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Tyg&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: Frilly-based tyg\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>The term 'frilly-based tyg' is used in some English archaeological literature<sup id=\"cite_ref-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup> to refer to a type of <a href=\"/wiki/Medieval\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Medieval\">medieval</a> and early <a href=\"/wiki/Post-medieval\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Post-medieval\">post-medieval</a> drinking mug or pitcher, usually <a href=\"/wiki/Pottery#Methods_of_shaping\" title=\"Pottery\">wheel-thrown</a> with a rounded belly and a straight or flared neck, which may have one or more handles. The 'frilly base' refers to the foot-ring of the mug, which after throwing was given an alternating bossed and indented form by manual shaping with fingers or thumbs. This style was popularized from c. 1300 onwards in hard-fired <a href=\"/wiki/Rhineland\" title=\"Rhineland\">Rhenish</a> wares, for example in <a href=\"/wiki/Ash_glaze\" title=\"Ash glaze\">ash-glazed</a> wares from <a href=\"/wiki/Siegburg\" title=\"Siegburg\">Siegburg</a>, near <a href=\"/wiki/Bonn\" title=\"Bonn\">Bonn</a>, Germany,<sup id=\"cite_ref-4\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup> and later in <a href=\"/wiki/Salt_glaze_pottery\" title=\"Salt glaze pottery\">salt-glazed</a> wares like those from <a href=\"/wiki/Raeren\" title=\"Raeren\">Raeren</a>, eastern Belgium.<sup id=\"cite_ref-5\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-5\">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup> These were imported to England in large quantities and were imitated in English stoneware and earthenware.    \n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Notes\">Notes</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Tyg&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: Notes\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-1\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">I.N. Hume, <i>A Guide to Artifacts of Colonial America</i> (Alfred A. Knopf, New York 1980), pp.102-04.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-2\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Hume 1980.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-3\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-3\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">e.g. E. Owles &amp; N. Smedley, 'Archaeology in Suffolk 1967' <i>Proceedings of the Suffolk Institute of Archaeology and History</i> XXXI Part 1 (1967), p. 78.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-4\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-4\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><a href=\"/wiki/Museum_of_London\" title=\"Museum of London\">Museum of London</a> Archive, Ceramics and Glass, <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://archive.museumoflondon.org.uk/ceramics/pages/subsubcategory.asp?subsubcat_id=835&amp;subsubcat_name=Siegburg&amp;page=1\">'Siegburg 1300-1800'</a></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-5\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-5\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Exeter City Council, Exeter time trail, <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.rammtimetrail.org.uk/Object/391/\">'A series of drinking jugs of Raeren stoneware'.</a></span>\n</li>\n</ol></div></div>\n<table class=\"metadata plainlinks stub\" role=\"presentation\" style=\"background:transparent\"><tbody><tr><td><span style=\"vertical-align: middle; background:transparent\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Flag_of_England.svg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"Flag of England\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/b/be/Flag_of_England.svg/30px-Flag_of_England.svg.png\" width=\"30\" height=\"18\" class=\"thumbborder\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/b/be/Flag_of_England.svg/45px-Flag_of_England.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/b/be/Flag_of_England.svg/60px-Flag_of_England.svg.png 2x\" data-file-width=\"800\" data-file-height=\"480\" /></a><span style=\"margin-left:-30px;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Hourglass_drawing.svg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"Hourglass icon\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c2/Hourglass_drawing.svg/23px-Hourglass_drawing.svg.png\" width=